<TITLE> Khaleda served legal notice to withdraw strike </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 26 (bdnews24.com)Opposition leader Khaleda Zia has been sent a legal notice asking her to withdraw the June 27 general strike. The notice, served by three persons on Wednesday, warns her that if the strike is not withdrawn, a petition will be filed with the High Court. The BNP chairperson called the dawn-to-dusk strike from the Paltan meeting on May 19. Azizul Haque Patwari, general secretary of Journalists Society for Human Rights and Welfare, M M Islam, vice president of Bangladesh Jatiyatabadi Ganatantrik Jote and Mahbub Alam Chowdhury of Shahrasti in Chandpur sent the notice. The other persons who were served the notice are BNP secretary general Khandakar Delwar Hossain, the home and law secretaries, and the inspector general of police. The three, claiming themselves as patriotic citizens, said in the notice that people and businessmen would be affected by the strike. People's lives will come to a standstill. A lot of people lost their lives and many shops and commercial institutions were damaged in violence during strikes in the past, the notice said. The strike will cause losses worth several millions of taka that will jeopardise the economy and investment will be affected as well, it said. The persons also alleged that no political parties work for the poor and the political leaders do not comply with the constitution. Supreme Court lawyer A B M Kamal Uddin Mia signed the legal notice. bdnews
